    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0f5e5b0d-8567-4008-a057-bd0ba25f1983",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 12-year-old boy who appears younger than his stated age, with a slender build, slightly hunched posture, and a quiet, reserved demeanor. He sits close to his mother during the consultation, frequently fidgeting with the hem of his shirt and avoiding direct eye contact. His speech is soft and measured, and he pauses often before answering questions, as if carefully weighing his words. Dark circles under his eyes hint at chronic sleep difficulties, and he occasionally bites his nails during pauses in conversation.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is described by his parents as a \"worrier\" — a child who has always been more anxious than his peers. He attends sixth grade at a local middle school, where he is academically diligent but frequently overwhelmed by tests, assignments, and social situations. He worries extensively about his grades, whether his friends like him, and potential disasters befalling his family. His worries shift rapidly from topic to topic and are difficult for him to control.\n\n{patientName} enjoys drawing, building LEGO sets, and playing video games, activities he often engages in alone as a way to decompress. He has a small but close friend group, though he often avoids social events out of fear of embarrassment or saying the wrong thing. He dislikes crowded or noisy environments such as school cafeterias and assemblies, and sometimes requests to eat lunch in the school library.\n\nPhysically, {patientName} frequently complains of stomachaches and headaches, particularly on school mornings. His mother notes he has trouble falling asleep most nights, lying awake ruminating about the next day. He is an only child and lives with both parents in a suburban home. His father works long hours as an engineer, and his mother is a part-time teacher who accompanies him to all his appointments. The family dynamic is warm but somewhat overprotective.\n\n{patientName} has no history of substance use and is not involved in organized sports, though his pediatrician has recommended more physical activity. He drinks sufficient water and eats regular meals, though his appetite is reduced on high-stress days. His parents are eager to find solutions and are open to both therapeutic and pharmacological options."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:e560f271-da32-44d4-841f-a90031d47208",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was born at term following an uncomplicated pregnancy and met all developmental milestones within normal limits. His parents first noticed signs of excessive worry around age 7, when he started school, but attributed it to a normal adjustment phase. Symptoms progressively worsened around age 10 with the transition to middle school, prompting referral to a pediatric psychologist at age 11. He was formally diagnosed with Generalized Anxiety Disorder (F41.1) following a comprehensive psychological evaluation using structured diagnostic interviews (SCARED and MASC-2 scales). He has no prior psychiatric hospitalizations.\n\n{patientName} has a history of childhood asthma, diagnosed at age 5, which is currently mild and well-controlled. He also has a history of allergic rhinitis, managed seasonally. He experienced a single febrile seizure at age 2 with no recurrence and no subsequent neurological sequelae. He has no known chronic gastrointestinal disease, though recurrent functional abdominal pain is documented and attributed to his anxiety. Vision is normal; hearing has not been formally tested recently.\n\nImmunizations are up to date. He has never smoked, consumed alcohol, or used any illicit substances. Family history is notable for anxiety disorders in his mother and paternal grandfather. {patientName} is currently engaged in weekly CBT sessions with a licensed child psychologist and has been attending for approximately 3 months. No pharmacotherapy for anxiety has been initiated to date. His pediatrician monitors him every 3 months."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}